title: fanoutqa: How many of the top five heaviest animals live in Africa? (f2d45721574984ef)

chat_history.content: How many of the top five heaviest animals live in Africa?

function.name: delegate
function.arguments: {"instructions": "Look up the top five heaviest animals and their primary habitats."}

chat_history.content:
Here are the top five heaviest animals and their primary habitats:

1. **African Bush Elephant**: Up to 10.1 tonnes (11.1 short tons)
   - **Habitat**: Savannas, forests, deserts, and marshes in sub-Saharan Africa.

2. **Asian Elephant**: 4.5 tonnes
   - **Habitat**: Forests, grasslands, and scrublands in Southeast Asia and parts of India.

3. **African Forest Elephant**: 2.7 tonnes
   - **Habitat**: Dense forests in Central and West Africa.

4. **White Rhinoceros**: 2 tonnes
   - **Habitat**: Grasslands and savannas in southern Africa.

5. **Indian Rhinoceros**: 1.9 tonnes
   - **Habitat**: Grasslands, forests, and floodplains in northern India and Nepal.</s>
chat_history.name: delegate

chat_history.content: 3 out of the top five heaviest animals live in Africa: the African Bush Elephant, the African Forest Elephant, and the White Rhinoceros.

functions.name: delegate
functions.desc:
Ask a capable helper for help looking up a piece of information or performing an action.
Do not simply repeat what the user said as instructions.
You should use this to break up complex user queries into multiple simpler steps.
NOTE: Helpers cannot see previous parts of your conversation.

instructions.description: Detailed instructions on what your helper should do to help you.

chat_history.content: Look up the top five heaviest animals and their primary habitats.

1. **African Bush Elephant**: Up to 10.1 tonnes (11.1 short tons)
2. **Asian Elephant**: 4.5 tonnes
3. **African Forest Elephant**: 2.7 tonnes
4. **White Rhinoceros**: 2 tonnes
5. **Indian Rhinoceros**: 1.9 tonnes</s>
chat_history.name: delegate

chat_history.content:
### Kangaroo

**Habitat:**
- Kangaroos are native to Australia.
- They inhabit a variety of environments, including savannas, scrublands, and forests.
- Some species, such as the red kangaroo, prefer open grasslands and deserts.

### Giant Panda

**Habitat:**
- Giant pandas are native to south central China, specifically in the provinces of Sichuan, Shaanxi, and Gansu.
- They primarily inhabit dense bamboo forests at high elevations, ranging from 4,000 to 11,000 feet.
- Giant pandas require large tracts of bamboo for food and shelter, which is why they are often found in remote, mountainous regions.

### Polar Bear

**Habitat:**
- Polar bears are native to the Arctic Circle, including areas in Canada, Alaska, Greenland, Russia, and Norway.
- They primarily inhabit sea ice, where they hunt for seals and other marine mammals.
- During the summer, when sea ice melts, polar bears may spend time on land in coastal regions.
- They are well-adapted to cold temperatures and rely on sea ice for survival.</s>
chat_history.name: delegate

chat_history.content:
Here are the top five heaviest animals and their primary habitats:

1. **African Bush Elephant**: Up to 10.1 tonnes (11.1 short tons)
   - **Habitat**: Savannas, forests, deserts, and marshes in sub-Saharan Africa.

2. **Asian Elephant**: 4.5 tonnes
   - **Habitat**: Forests, grasslands, and scrublands in Southeast Asia and parts of India.

3. **African Forest Elephant**: 2.7 tonnes
   - **Habitat**: Dense forests in Central and West Africa.

4. **White Rhinoceros**: 2 tonnes
   - **Habitat**: Grasslands and savannas in southern Africa.

5. **Indian Rhinoceros**: 1.9 tonnes
   - **Habitat**: Grasslands, forests, and floodplains in northern India and Nepal.</s>

Ask a capable helper for help looking up a piece of information or performing an action.
Do not simply repeat what the user said as instructions.
You should use this to break up complex user queries into multiple simpler steps.
NOTE: Helpers cannot see previous parts of your conversation.

chat_history.content:
# Largest and Heaviest Animals

## Largest Animals

### Mammals

The blue whale is the largest mammal of all time, with the largest known specimen being 33.6 m (110.2 ft) long and the largest weighted specimen being 190 tonnes. The extinct whale species Perucetus colossus was shorter than the blue whale, at 17.0–20.1 meters (55.8–65.9 ft) but it is estimated to have rivaled or surpassed it in weight, at 85–340 tonnes. At the highest estimates, this would make Perucetus the heaviest known animal in history.

### Birds

The largest extant species of bird measured by mass is the common ostrich (Struthio camelus), closely followed by the Somali ostrich (Struthio molybdophanes). A male ostrich can reach a height of 2.8 metres (9.2 feet) and weigh over 156.8 kg (346 lb). The bird with the largest wingspan is the wandering albatross (Diomedea exulans) of the Sub-Antarctic oceans. The largest dimensions found in this species are an approximate head-to-tail length of 1.44 m (4.7 ft) and a wingspan of 3.65 m (12.0 ft).

## Heaviest Animals

### Land Mammals

The heaviest land mammal is the African bush elephant, which has a weight of up to 10.1 t (11.1 short tons). It measures 10–13 ft at the shoulder and consumes around 230 kg (500 lb) of vegetation a day. Its tusks have been known to reach 2.7 m (9 ft) in length, although in modern populations they are most commonly recorded at a length of 0.6–0.9 m (2 ft 0 in– 2 ft 11 in). The average walking speed of an elephant is 7.2 km/h (4.5 mph), but they can run at recorded speeds of up to 24 km/h (15 mph).

Other heavy land mammals include:

- Asian elephant: 4.5 tonnes
- African forest elephant: 2.7 tonnes
- White rhinoceros: 2 tonnes
- Indian rhinoceros: 1.9 tonnes
- Hippopotamus: 1.8 tonnes
- Black rhinoceros: 1.1 tonnes
- Javan rhinoceros: 1.75 tonnes
- Giraffe: 1 tonne
- Gaur: 0.95 tonnes

### Birds

The largest extant species of bird measured by mass is the common ostrich (Struthio camelus), closely followed by the Somali ostrich (Struthio molybdophanes). A male ostrich can reach a height of 2.8 metres (9.2 feet) and weigh over 156.8 kg (346 lb).

Other heavy birds include:

- Wandering albatross: 3.65 m (12.0 ft) wingspan
- Emperor penguin: 46 kg (101 lb)
- Harpy eagle: 10 kg (22 lb)
- Steller's sea eagle: 12.7 kg (28 lb)
- Giant ibis: 4.2 kg (9.3 lb)
- Speckled mousebird: 57 g (2 oz)

These lists provide a comprehensive overview of the largest and heaviest animals, both mammals and birds, highlighting their impressive sizes and weights.</s>

functions.name: delegate
functions.desc:
Ask a capable helper for help looking up a piece of information or performing an action.
Do not simply repeat what the user said as instructions.
You should use this to break up complex user queries into multiple simpler steps.
NOTE: Helpers cannot see previous parts of your conversation.

instructions.description: Detailed instructions on what your helper should do to help you.

functions.name: search
functions.desc: Search Wikipedia for an article with the given title, and get its content. If no such article is found, return similar article names.

chat_history.content: Identify the primary habitats of each animal.

function.name: delegate
function.arguments: {"instructions": "Search Wikipedia for the following animals: Polar Bear, Panda, and Kangaroo. Summarize the primary habitat for each animal."}

chat_history.content:
### Kangaroo

**Habitat:**
- Kangaroos are native to Australia.
- They inhabit a variety of environments, including savannas, scrublands, and forests.
- Some species, such as the red kangaroo, prefer open grasslands and deserts.

### Giant Panda

**Habitat:**
- Giant pandas are native to south central China, specifically in the provinces of Sichuan, Shaanxi, and Gansu.
- They primarily inhabit dense bamboo forests at high elevations, ranging from 4,000 to 11,000 feet.
- Giant pandas require large tracts of bamboo for food and shelter, which is why they are often found in remote, mountainous regions.

### Polar Bear

**Habitat:**
- Polar bears are native to the Arctic Circle, including areas in Canada, Alaska, Greenland, Russia, and Norway.
- They primarily inhabit sea ice, where they hunt for seals and other marine mammals.
- During the summer, when sea ice melts, polar bears may spend time on land in coastal regions.
- They are well-adapted to cold temperatures and rely on sea ice for survival.</s>

<fragment>

The polar bear is considered to be a vulnerable species by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) with an estimated total population of 22,000 to 31,000 individuals. Its biggest threats are climate change, pollution and energy development. Climate change has caused a decline in sea ice, giving the polar bear less access to its favoured prey and increasing the risk of malnutrition and starvation. Less sea ice also means that the bears must spend more time on land, increasing conflicts with people. Polar bears have been hunted, both by native and non-native peoples, for their coats, meat and other items. They have been kept in captivity in zoos and circuses and are prevalent in art, folklore, religion and modern culture.

chat_history.content:
### Kangaroo

**Habitat:**
- Kangaroos are native to Australia.
- They inhabit a variety of environments, including savannas, scrublands, and forests.
- Some species, such as the red kangaroo, prefer open grasslands and deserts.

### Giant Panda

**Habitat:**
- Giant pandas are native to south central China, specifically in the provinces of Sichuan, Shaanxi, and Gansu.
- They primarily inhabit dense bamboo forests at high elevations, ranging from 4,000 to 11,000 feet.
- Giant pandas require large tracts of bamboo for food and shelter, which is why they are often found in remote, mountainous regions.

### Polar Bear

**Habitat:**
- Polar bears are native to the Arctic Circle, including areas in Canada, Alaska, Greenland, Russia, and Norway.
- They primarily inhabit sea ice, where they hunt for seals and other marine mammals.
- During the summer, when sea ice melts, polar bears may spend time on land in coastal regions.
- They are well-adapted to cold temperatures and rely on sea ice for survival.</s>

## Vertebrates[edit]


</fragment>
<fragment>

The African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*) is the largest living land animal. A native of various open habitats in sub-Saharan Africa, males weigh about 6.0 tonnes (13,200 lb) on average.[9] The largest elephant ever recorded was shot in Angola in 1974. It was a male measuring 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) from trunk to tail and 4.17 metres (13.7 ft) lying on its side in a projected line from the highest point of the shoulder, to the base of the forefoot, indicating a standing shoulder height of 3.96 metres (13.0 ft). This male had a computed weight of 10.4 tonnes.[1]




## Heaviest living animals[edit]


The heaviest living animals are all whales. Since no scale can accommodate the whole body of a large whale, most have been weighed by parts.






</fragment>
<fragment>

### Mammals (Mammalia)[edit]


Main article: List of largest mammals

![](image)Size of *Paraceratherium* (dark grey) compared to a human and other rhinos (though one study suggests *Palaeoloxodon namadicus* may have been a larger land mammal)
The blue whale is the largest mammal of all time, with the largest known specimen being 33.6 m (110.2 ft) long and the largest weighted specimen being 190 tonnes.[53][54] The extinct whale species *Perucetus colossus* was shorter than the blue whale, at 17.0–20.1 meters (55.8–65.9 ft) but it is estimated to have rivaled or surpassed it in weight, at 85–340 tonnes. At the highest estimates, this would make *Perucetus* the heaviest known animal in history.[7]


</fragment>
<fragment>
The largest ceratopsians were *Triceratops* and its ancestor *Eotriceratops* from the late Cretaceous of North America. Both estimated to have reached about 9 m (30 ft) in length[154] and weighed 12 tonnes.[155][156]
#### Birds (Aves)[edit]


Main article: List of largest birds

![](image)The common ostrich is the largest living bird.
The largest living bird, a member of the Struthioniformes, is the common ostrich (*Struthio camelus*), from the plains of Africa. A large male ostrich can reach a height of 2.8 m (9.2 ft) and weigh over 156 kg (344 lb).[157] A mass of 200 kg (440 lb) has been cited for the common ostrich but no wild ostriches of this weight have been verified.[158] Eggs laid by the ostrich can weigh 1.4 kg (3.1 lb) and are the largest eggs in the world today.[*citation needed*]


</fragment>
</document>

<title>List of heaviest land mammals</title>
<fragment>
The **heaviest land** mammal is the African bush elephant, which has a weight of up to 10.1 t (11.1 short tons). It measures 10–13 ft at the shoulder and consumes around 230 kg (500 lb) of vegetation a day. Its tusks have been known to reach 2.7 m (9 ft) in length, although in modern populations they are most commonly recorded at a length of 0.6–0.9 m (2 ft 0 in – 2 ft 11 in).[1] The average walking speed of an elephant is 7.2 km/h (4.5 mph), but they can run at recorded speeds of up to 24 km/h (15 mph).[2]

<document>
<title>List of largest birds</title>
<fragment>
The largest extant species of bird measured by mass is the common ostrich (*Struthio camelus*), closely followed by the Somali ostrich (*Struthio molybdophanes*). A male ostrich can reach a height of 2.8 metres (9.2 feet) and weigh over 156.8 kg (346 lb),[1] A mass of 200 kg (440 lb) has been cited for the ostrich but no wild ostriches of this weight have been verified.[2] Ostrich eggs are the largest of any bird, averaging 1.4 kg (3.1 lb).[3]


The bird with the largest wingspan is the wandering albatross (*Diomedea exulans*) of the Sub-Antarctic oceans. The largest dimensions found in this species are an approximate head-to-tail length of 1.44 m (4.7 ft) and a wingspan of 3.65 m (12.0 ft).




## Largest extinct birds

[edit]


### Table of heaviest extinct bird species

## Largest extant birds

[edit]

### Table of heaviest extant bird species

[edit]

The following table is a list of the heaviest extant bird species based on maximum reported or reliable mass, with the average weight is also given for comparison. These species are almost all flightless, having denser bones and heavier bodies. Flightless birds comprise less than 1% of all extant bird species.






</fragment>
<fragment>
* A prehistoric, flightless family, sometimes called (incorrectly) "giant megapodes" (*Sylviornis*) of New Caledonia were the most massive galliformes ever, with lengths of up to 1.7 m (5.6 ft) weights up to approximately 40 kg (88 lb).[96]


#### Loons (Gaviiformes)

[edit]

* The largest species on average is the yellow-billed loon (*Gavia adamsii*) of the Arctic, at up to 1 m (3.3 ft) and 7 kg (15 lb). One exceptionally large North American Great northern diver (*Gavia immer*) was weighed at 8 kg (18 lb), heavier than any recorded yellow-billed loon. Wingspans of the largest loons can reach 1.52 m (5.0 ft).[97]


![](image)Alongside the great bustard, the kori bustard is the heaviest extant flying bird.
#### Cranes and allies (Gruiformes)

[edit]


</fragment>
<fragment>
* The largest living member of this order, in terms of length and height, is the secretarybird (*Sagittarius serpentarius*) of sub-Saharan Africa. It measures 0.9–1.3 m (3.0–4.3 ft) in height and 1.2–1.5 m (3.9–4.9 ft) in length. Its wingspan can reach 1.2–1.35 m (3.9–4.4 ft) and have a weight of 2.3–4.27 kg (5.1–9.4 lb).[51]
* The largest predatory bird, specifically the largest eagle, is a source of contention.
	+ The harpy eagle (*Harpia harpyja*) of neotropical forests is often cited as the most massive eagle, with wild females up to 10 kg (22 lb) in weight and captive females occasionally growing to weights of over 12 kg (26 lb).[42]
	+ The Steller's sea eagle (*Haliaeetus pelagicus*) of Asia's North Pacific, with unconfirmed weights of up to 12.7 kg (28 lb), and an average weight of 6.7 kg (15 lb), is sometimes regarded as the heaviest eagle.

</fragment>
<fragment>

![](image)The emperor penguin is one of the heaviest living birds as well as the largest penguin.
#### Penguins (Sphenisciformes)

[edit]

* The largest species of Sphenisciformes is the emperor penguin (*Aptenodytes forsteri*) of the Antarctic, with a maximum height of 1.35 m (4.4 ft) and a weight of 46 kg (101 lb).[42] The next largest living species is the king penguin, which grows to a maximum of 1 m (3.3 ft) in height and 18 kg (40 lb) in weight.[137] Now extinct, *Anthropornis nordenskjoeldi*, is believed to have reached a height of 1.8 m (5.9 ft) and a weight of up to 108 kg (238 lb).[138]


![](image)The Eurasian eagle-owl is one of the biggest owls.
#### Owls (Strigiformes)

[edit]


</fragment>
<fragment>
* Many of the largest flying birds in the fossil record may have been members of the Ciconiiformes. The heaviest flying bird ever, *Argentavis magnificens*, is part of a group, the teratorns, that is considered an ally of the New World vultures.[80]
* The largest ibis is the giant ibis (*Thaumatibis gigantea*). Adults can grow to 102–106 cm (40–42 in) long, with a standing height of up to 100 cm (39 in) and are estimated to weigh approximately 4.2 kg (9.3 lb). Among standard measurements, the wing chord is 52.3–57 cm (20.6–22.4 in), the tail is 30 cm (12 in), the tarsus is 11 cm (4.3 in) and the culmen is 20.8–23.4 cm (8.2–9.2 in). The crested ibis (*Nipponia nippon*) of Japan is as large as 78.5 cm (30.9 in) in height and 30.9 cm (12.2 in) in length.


#### Mousebirds (Coliiformes)

[edit]

* The largest mousebird species, the speckled mousebird (*Colius striatus*), weighs 2 ounces (57 g) with a height of over 14 inches (36 cm).[81]


</fragment>
</document>

chat_history.content:
# Largest and Heaviest Animals

## Largest Animals

### Mammals

The blue whale is the largest mammal of all time, with the largest known specimen being 33.6 m (110.2 ft) long and the largest weighted specimen being 190 tonnes. The extinct whale species Perucetus colossus was shorter than the blue whale, at 17.0–20.1 meters (55.8–65.9 ft) but it is estimated to have rivaled or surpassed it in weight, at 85–340 tonnes. At the highest estimates, this would make Perucetus the heaviest known animal in history.

### Birds

The largest extant species of bird measured by mass is the common ostrich (Struthio camelus), closely followed by the Somali ostrich (Struthio molybdophanes). A male ostrich can reach a height of 2.8 metres (9.2 feet) and weigh over 156.8 kg (346 lb). The bird with the largest wingspan is the wandering albatross (Diomedea exulans) of the Sub-Antarctic oceans. The largest dimensions found in this species are an approximate head-to-tail length of 1.44 m (4.7 ft) and a wingspan of 3.65 m (12.0 ft).

## Heaviest Animals

### Land Mammals

The heaviest land mammal is the African bush elephant, which has a weight of up to 10.1 t (11.1 short tons). It measures 10–13 ft at the shoulder and consumes around 230 kg (500 lb) of vegetation a day. Its tusks have been known to reach 2.7 m (9 ft) in length, although in modern populations they are most commonly recorded at a length of 0.6–0.9 m (2 ft 0 in– 2 ft 11 in). The average walking speed of an elephant is 7.2 km/h (4.5 mph), but they can run at recorded speeds of up to 24 km/h (15 mph).

Other heavy land mammals include:

- Asian elephant: 4.5 tonnes
- African forest elephant: 2.7 tonnes
- White rhinoceros: 2 tonnes
- Indian rhinoceros: 1.9 tonnes
- Hippopotamus: 1.8 tonnes
- Black rhinoceros: 1.1 tonnes
- Javan rhinoceros: 1.75 tonnes
- Giraffe: 1 tonne
- Gaur: 0.95 tonnes

### Birds

The largest extant species of bird measured by mass is the common ostrich (Struthio camelus), closely followed by the Somali ostrich (Struthio molybdophanes). A male ostrich can reach a height of 2.8 metres (9.2 feet) and weigh over 156.8 kg (346 lb).

Other heavy birds include:

- Wandering albatross: 3.65 m (12.0 ft) wingspan
- Emperor penguin: 46 kg (101 lb)
- Harpy eagle: 10 kg (22 lb)
- Steller's sea eagle: 12.7 kg (28 lb)
- Giant ibis: 4.2 kg (9.3 lb)
- Speckled mousebird: 57 g (2 oz)

These lists provide a comprehensive overview of the largest and heaviest animals, both mammals and birds, highlighting their impressive sizes and weights.</s>

functions.name: delegate
functions.desc:
Ask a capable helper for help looking up a piece of information or performing an action.
Do not simply repeat what the user said as instructions.
You should use this to break up complex user queries into multiple simpler steps.
NOTE: Helpers cannot see previous parts of your conversation.

instructions.description: Detailed instructions on what your helper should do to help you.

functions.name: search
functions.desc: Search Wikipedia for an article with the given title, and get its content. If no such article is found, return similar article names.
